# **Scope**

| Product Summary *Briefly recap what the product is, focusing on what’s relevant to this change* |
| :---- |
| Telecom companies struggle with fragmented data spread across multiple legacy systems, proprietary databases, and third-party platforms. Many operators find themselves locked into outdated infrastructure, making it difficult to unify data, launch new services, and integrate with modern digital ecosystems. Existing integration solutions are often complex, costly, and require extensive customization, leading to long implementation times and ongoing maintenance overhead. BSS Magic solves this problem by providing a streamlined, opinionated platform that maps telecom data from any source directly into an Ontology that is exposed via standardized and open APIs. Designed for simplicity and efficiency, BSS Magic enables telecom operators to modernize their data infrastructure without the typical integration headaches. With an intuitive interface, AI-powered automated data transformation, and strict adherence to a standardized API framework, BSS Magic accelerates digital transformation and ensures seamless interoperability across BSS, OSS, and partner ecosystems. By leveraging AI to intelligently map, clean, and optimize data, BSS Magic significantly reduces the time and effort required for integration. This allows telcos to focus on innovation, improve operational efficiency, and unlock new revenue opportunities with minimal effort. Think of BSS Magic as an opinionated Palantir Foundry for Telco. |

| Problem Summary *What is the problem, deficiency, or gap which will be addressed by this spec?* |
| ----- |
| **Background** |
| Several efforts have explored what BSS Magic could look and act like. Based on what we have learned so far, we want to begin work on the production product. So far, we have defined BSS Magic as a stack that consists of: Adapters that map customer data sources into the BSS Magic Ontology (TM Forum SID model) An intelligence layer that leverages AI to create semantic understanding of data A set tools to build solutions on top of all this information ![][image1] This is the first official BSS Magic spec, which will lay the foundation of the production by building the BSS Magic Ontology. The “Adapter” layer that exposes the customer’s data via TM Forum APIs. |
| **1-sentence Goal** |
| Build the Adapter layer of BSS Magic |

# **Solution Architecture**

| Diagram  *This diagram shows how the product will look after the change.*  |
| ----- |
| ![][image2] |

| Solution Summary *In a nutshell, how are we solving the problem?* |
| :---- |
| Separate runtime and design-time into distinct components with potentially different architectures Use a declarative approach to define the ontology mapping between TMF APIs and customer data sources Implement AI using Amazon Bedrock high-level primitives Secure APIs using Amazon Cognito AI is used to make the ontology mapping process 100x faster than manual work: **Automated Mappings** – AI analyzes the customer’s data sources and maps to TM Forum based on the TM Forum Business Process Framework, schema, semantics, and best practices **Guided Refinement** – AI helps users review, validate, and modify mappings through an intuitive UI **Querying Data** – AI can interrogate APIs, inspect sample payloads, and generate test queries to validate mappings **Ensuring Consistency** – AI identifies inconsistencies and flags potential data mismatches before they impact runtime behavior |

| Engineering Insights *What important insights / guidelines can you provide to engineering?* |  |
| :---- | ----- |
| There are three key outputs from this spec: Declarative ontology mapping  An AI integration that can understand and generate the declarative ontology mapping  A runtime that can expose the customer data via TM Forum APIs by using the declarative ontology mapping |  |

| ITD 1 \- Separate runtime and design-time into distinct components |  |
| :---- | :---- |
| **THE PROBLEM** | There are two aspects to this spec: A design time aspect where customer data sources must be mapped to the TM Forum ontology, and a runtime aspect where TM Forum APIs are hosted and call into the customer data sources to fulfill the requests. Should the runtime and design-time aspects of BSS Magic be combined or separated? |
| **OPTIONS CONSIDERED(Decision in bold)** | Combine runtime and design-time into a single unified system **Separate runtime and design-time into distinct components** |
| **REASONING** | Separating runtime and design-time allows for optimized scalability, ensuring high availability for runtime operations while keeping design-time processes resource-efficient. It enhances security and stability by preventing real-time disruptions from configuration changes. This separation provides flexibility for different user roles, improves performance by keeping runtime lightweight, and future-proofs the architecture for independent evolution of mapping logic, AI models, and deployment strategies. |
| **P2 FEEDBACK** | The runtime will have the TM Forum APIs as its “user-plane”, and have minimal “control-plane” operations \- perhaps only the ability to update the ontology mapping. The design time will have APIs that are used to build the web UI that creates ontology mappings via AI assistance. It can dynamically configure and query the runtime to test the ontology during the mapping process. |

| ITD 2 \- Use a declarative approach to define the ontology mapping between TMF APIs and customer data sources |  |
| :---- | :---- |
| **THE PROBLEM** | What form should the ontology mapping between TMF APIs and customer data sources take? |
| **OPTIONS CONSIDERED(Decision in bold)** | **Declarative Approach (configuration based)** Imperative Approach (code based) Hybrid Approach |
| **REASONING** | A declarative approach simplifies integration by focusing on *what* needs to be mapped rather than *how* it is processed. This improves maintainability, allows for AI-driven assistance, and enables dynamic updates without modifying core logic. It also enhances portability, version control, and interoperability across different systems. While a hybrid approach may be necessary for edge cases, keeping the core mapping declarative ensures scalability, automation, and reduced operational complexity. |
| **P2 FEEDBACK** | We will leave the exact form of the mapping configuration to the implementation.  An [example](#mapping-example) is provided in the appendix as one possible starting point. |

| IF 3 \- Implement AI using Amazon Bedrock high-level primitives |  |
| :---- | :---- |
| **DESCRIPTION** | Use most appropriate high-level primitives from Amazon Bedrock to implement the AI assisted ontology mapping. For example, do not build your own agent framework, build on top of [Bedrock Agents](https://aws.amazon.com/bedrock/agents/).  |
| **P2 FEEDBACK** | We must seed the AI implementation with everything it needs to know about: TMF APIs \- documentation, schemas, [communities](https://engage.tmforum.org/communities/allcommunities), etc. The ontology mapping format and what information is required to complete it It can interrogate the user for information on their APIs |

| IF 4 \- Secure APIs using Amazon Cognito |  |
| :---- | :---- |
| **DESCRIPTION** | Secure both runtime and ontology APIs using Amazon Cognito. Separate user pools should be used for each. |

| IF 5 \- Other technology choices |  |
| :---- | :---- |
| **DESCRIPTION** | This spec is intentionally light on many technology choices because there are so many unanswered questions about which direction this initial implementation will take. For example, we wouldn’t want to specify a programming language and therefore exclude the perfect integration framework. That said, we provide the following guidance: It is preferable to use a strongly typed language like Java that has a rich set of 3rd party libraries Use whatever compute is simplest Use whatever database is simplest Use an integration framework, such as Apache Camel or Trino, to implement the mapping plumbing For example, one potential approach would be to create a full SQL Schema from the TM Forum SID, map the TM Forum APIs onto that schema, and then use Trino to implement the SQL tables by calling into each customer data source. We will make long term decisions after the initial functionality is in place and we understand the usage patterns.  DO NOT over design or prematurely optimize \- we are looking for functionality. |

# **Functional Test Cases**

| Test Case 1 \- AI-Generated Initial Ontology Mapping |  |
| :---- | :---- |
| **DESCRIPTION** | Validate that AI can automatically generate a mapping between a customer’s data source and the TM Forum API. |
| **PRE-REQUISITES** | Sample customer data sources from two products, each with predefined sample data: Totogi Charging CloudSense STL OneBill LogiSense |
| **STEPS** | Connect to a sample customer data source Collect information from the customer on the API/Schema of the data source, documentation, and other information about their goals. Allow AI to analyze the schema and generate an initial mapping Review the suggested mappings via the UI Validate that the majority of AI-generated mappings align with expected fields and transformations Repeat for the remaining data sources |
| **EXPECTED OUTCOME** | AI successfully generates a mapping suggestion. Suggested mapping includes relevant schema fields from the customer’s data source. No critical mismatches between customer data and TM Forum API fields. |

| Test Case 2 \- AI-Assisted Mapping Refinement |  |
| :---- | :---- |
| **DESCRIPTION** | Ensure that users can interactively refine AI-generated mappings and validate the updates. |
| **PRE-REQUISITES** | AI-generated mapping from Test Case 1 Access to the ontology mapping UI |
| **STEPS** | Open the AI-generated mapping in the UI Modify field mappings manually (e.g., rename a field, change a transformation rule) Save and apply the refined mapping Run a test transformation with sample customer data Verify that updates are correctly applied to the output |
| **EXPECTED OUTCOME** | User modifications are saved and persist correctly AI does not overwrite user-defined changes unless the user requests or confirms the operation Output from the test transformation correctly reflects user modifications |

| Test Case 3 \- AI-Driven Consistency Check & Validation |  |
| :---- | :---- |
| **DESCRIPTION** | Verify that AI can detect and flag inconsistencies in an ontology mapping before deployment. |
| **PRE-REQUISITES** | A completed ontology mapping with manually introduced errors (e.g., inconsistent field types, missing required fields). |
| **STEPS** | Open the AI-generated mapping in the UI and access the test ontology Allow AI to analyze the mapping for inconsistencies Review AI-generated warnings and recommendations Apply AI-suggested corrections where applicable Re-run validation to ensure errors are resolved |
| **EXPECTED OUTCOME** | AI correctly identifies missing or inconsistent mappings AI provides clear and actionable recommendations to correct issues After fixing errors, the mapping passes validation without warnings |

| Test Case 4 \- Runtime Execution of Ontology Mapping |  |
| :---- | :---- |
| **DESCRIPTION** | Validate that the runtime correctly processes incoming TM Forum API requests and maps them to customer data sources using the defined ontology mapping. |
| **PRE-REQUISITES** | A validated ontology mapping The mapped customer data sources accessible via API |
| **STEPS** | Deploy a predefined ontology mapping to the runtime. Send read and write requests to TM Forum API endpoints \- e.g.: POST /accountManagement/v5/partyAccount GET /accountManagement/v5/partyAccount/{id} PATCH /accountManagement/v5/partyAccount/{id} Verify that the request is correctly translated to a call to the mapped customer API(s) Check that the response is transformed according to the ontology mapping Validate that all expected data fields are correctly populated in the TM Forum API response Validate the mapped APIs pass the TM Forum conformance tests |
| **EXPECTED OUTCOME** | The runtime successfully translates the TM Forum API request into calls to customer data sources. The response is correctly transformed and formatted according to the ontology mapping. No data loss or incorrect mappings occur in the returned response. Hosted runtime APIs pass the TM Forum conformance tests |

# **Appendices**

## **Mapping Example** {#mapping-example}

Below is a hypothetical example of what the declarative ontology mapping might look like.  This is just one possible approach, there may be others that are better.  We will learn which approaches work best by using them in real world situations.

```javascript
{
  "mappings": [
    {
      "name": "retrievePartyAccount",
      "upstream": {
        "method": "GET",
        "path": "/accountManagement/v5/partyAccount/{id}",
      },
      "downstream": [
        {
          "method": "GET",
          "path": "/customer/profile/${upstream.parameters.id}",
          "response": {
            "transform": {
              "id": "${response.customerId}",
              "href": "/accountManagement/v5/partyAccount/${response.customerId}",
              "accountType": "individual",
              "name": "${response.firstName} ${response.lastName}",
              "state": "${response.status}"
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "getBillingInfo",
          "method": "GET",
          "path": "/billing/accounts/${upstream.parameters.id}",
          "response": {
            "merge": true,
            "transform": {
              "creditLimit": "${response.maxCredit}",
              "paymentStatus": "${response.accountStatus}"
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "updatePartyAccount",
      "upstream": {
        "method": "PATCH",
        "path": "/accountManagement/v5/partyAccount/{id}",
      },
      "downstream": [
        {
          "name": "updateCustomerProfile",
          "method": "PUT",
          "path": "/customer/profile/${upstream.parameters.id}",
          "transform": {
            "firstName": "${request.body.name.split(' ')[0]}",
            "lastName": "${request.body.name.split(' ')[1]}",
            "status": "${request.body.state}"
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "updateBillingAccount",
          "method": "PATCH",
          "path": "/billing/accounts/${upstream.parameters.id}",
          "condition": "${request.body.creditLimit !== undefined}",
          "transform": {
            "maxCredit": "${request.body.creditLimit}",
            "accountStatus": "${request.body.paymentStatus}"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```
